timestamp.description: The Unix epoch (or Unix time or POSIX time or Unix timestamp) is the number of seconds that have elapsed since January 1, 1970 (midnight UTC/GMT).

instantaneous.description:
> **Unit:** 
>
>Hertz (Hz)
>
>Hertz (Hz) measures the frequency of oscillationin the electrical grid, indicating the number of cycles per second. In standard systems, common frequencies are 50 Hz or 60 Hz.

frequency.name: Frequency
frequency.description: The number of cycles per second in an alternating current (AC) system, measured in Hertz (Hz).

rms.name: RMS
rms.description:
Voltage RMS (Root Mean Square), the square root of the arithmetic mean of the squared values of a periodic waveform. It represents the effective value of voltage in an AC system.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Volt (V)
>
>Volt (V) is a unit of electric potential difference between two points in an AC circuit.

waveform_peak.name: Waveform Peak
waveform_peak.description:
Maximum value of the voltage within individual cycles during a 1-second timeframe. In a 230V AC line, the nominal peak voltage may reach 325 V.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Volt (V)
>
>Volt (V) is a unit of electric potential difference between two points in an AC circuit.

crest_factor.name: Crest Factor
crest_factor.description:
Ratio of the peak value to the RMS value of a waveform. A pure sine wave has a crest factor of 1.414.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Crest factor (CF)
>
>Crest factor is a dimensionless ratio between the peak and RMS values of a waveform.

rms.name: Relative to RMS
rms.description:
THD-V based on RMS. Indicates quality of voltage. High values can affect sensitive equipment.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Percent (% THDr)
>
>THD relative to RMS voltage, expressed as a percentage, denoted as % THDr.

fundamental.name: Relative to Fundamental
fundamental.description:
THD-V based on Fundamental frequency. Focuses on distortion from base AC frequency. Useful for filtering decisions.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Percent (% THDf)
>
>THD relative to the fundamental frequency, expressed as a percentage, denoted as % THDf.

thd.name: THD-V
thd.description: THD-V (Total Harmonic Distortion in Voltage) measures how much voltage waveform deviates from a pure sine wave. High levels usually originate from supply distortions or nonlinear loads. Can affect sensitive devices.

voltage.name: Voltage
voltage.description: Voltage in an AC system is the electric potential difference between two points in the circuit. It oscillates between positive and negative values and can be measured as line-to-line (L-L) or line-to-neutral (L-N).

rms.name: RMS
rms.description:
Current RMS (Root Mean Square) is the square root of the arithmetic mean of the squared values of a periodic waveform. It represents the effective value of current in an AC system.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Ampere (A)
>
>Ampere (A) is the unit of electric current in AC systems, indicating the flow of charge.

waveform_peak.name: Waveform Peak
waveform_peak.description:
Maximum value of the current within individual cycles during a 1-second timeframe. In a 10A AC line, the nominal peak current may reach 14.14A.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Ampere (A)
>
>Ampere (A) is the unit of electric current in AC systems, indicating the flow of charge.

crest_factor.name: Crest Factor
crest_factor.description:
Ratio of the peak value to the RMS value of a waveform. A pure sine wave has a crest factor of 1.414.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Crest factor (CF)
>
>Crest factor is a dimensionless ratio between the peak and RMS values of a waveform.

rms.name: Relative to RMS
rms.description:
THD-I based on RMS. Shows distortion in current flow. High values can cause heating in conductors.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Percent (% THDr)
>
>THD relative to RMS voltage, expressed as a percentage, denoted as % THDr.

fundamental.name: Relative to Fundamental
fundamental.description:
THD-I based on Fundamental frequency. Useful for targeting specific harmonics causing issues in a system.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Percent (% THDf)
>
>THD relative to the fundamental frequency, expressed as a percentage, denoted as % THDf.

thd.name: THD-I
thd.description: THD-I (Total Harmonic Distortion in Current) indicates how much the current waveform strays from a sine wave. Often caused by demand-side nonlinear loads. Can result in overheating and equipment stress.

current.name: Current
current.description: Measures related to the the flow of electric charge in a circuit.

active.name: Active
active.description:
Active power is the real power that does actual work, like turning a motor or powering a device. Measured in watts (W), it's the primary factor for energy billing.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Watt (W)
>
>Watt (W) is the unit of active power in AC electrical systems, used to quantify the rate of energy transfer.

reactive.name: Reactive
reactive.description:
Reactive power doesn't do work but supports the magnetic and electric fields in AC systems. Measured in volt-amperes reactive (VAR), it's essential for system stability but can lead to inefficiencies.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Volt-Ampere Reactive (VAR)
>
>Volt-Ampere Reactive (VAR) measures reactive power in AC systems. Important in systems with inductive loads like motors and transformers; excessive VAR can lead to higher utility charges and necessitates more robust infrastructure.

apparent.name: Apparent
apparent.description:
Apparent power represents the total power flow in an AC circuit, combining active and reactive power. Measured in volt-amperes (VA), it's useful for sizing equipment and wiring but doesn't reflect real energy use.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Volt-Ampere (VA)
>
>Volt-Ampere (VA) is the unit for apparent power in an AC electrical system.

total.name: Total
total.description:
The overall measure of electrical system efficiency, considering both displacement and distortion factors. A low total power factor may require infrastructure upgrades or power factor correction devices.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Power Factor (λ)
>
>Dimensionless ratio of active power (W) to apparent power (VA) in an AC circuit. It combines both displacement and distortion effects.

power_factor.name: Power Factor
power_factor.description: Power factor measures the efficiency of converting electrical power to useful work, combining both the phase displacement between current and voltage and harmonic distortion. A low power factor necessitates larger network infrastructure to manage inefficiencies.

power.name: Power
power.description: Power in an AC system is the rate of energy transfer, affected by both voltage and current. It consists of active, reactive, and apparent components, each measured in specific units.

imported.name: Imported
imported.description:
Energy drawn from the grid. Directly impacts electricity bills. Typically measured in kWh.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Watt-hour (Wh)
>
>Watt-hour (Wh) units measure energy doing useful work, directly linked to billing.

exported.name: Exported
exported.description:
Energy sent back to the grid. Can generate credits or offset costs. Typically measured in kWh.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Watt-hour (Wh)
>
>Watt-hour (Wh) units measure energy doing useful work, directly linked to billing.

active.name: Active
active.description: Active energy represents the actual work done. Directly impacts billing as utilities usually charge based on this consumption.

imported.name: Imported
imported.description:
Reactive energy drawn from the grid to maintain magnetic fields in inductive loads. Could lead to power factor penalties. Typically measured in kVARh.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Volt-Ampere Reactive hour (VARh)
>
>Volt-Ampere Reactive hour (VARh) units measure energy stored and returned to the system.

exported.name: Exported
exported.description:
Reactive energy sent back to the grid. Not usually credited. May indicate over-compensation of power factor correction devices. Typically measured in kVARh.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Volt-Ampere Reactive hour (VARh)
>
>Volt-Ampere Reactive hour (VARh) units measure energy stored and returned to the system.

reactive.name: Reactive
reactive.description: Reactive energy signifies energy stored and released back to the grid. Some utilities may charge for excessive reactive energy since it can burden the system without doing useful work.

imported.name: Imported
imported.description:
Apparent energy drawn from the grid. Can be a factor in demand or capacity charges. Typically measured in kVAh.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Volt-Ampere hour (VAh)
>
>Volt-Ampere hour (VAh) units measure the vector sum of active and reactive energy, provides overall view of energy flow.

exported.name: Exported
exported.description:
Apparent energy sent back to the grid. Rarely credited, but informs system's export capacity. Typically measured in kVAh.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Volt-Ampere hour (VAh)
>
>Volt-Ampere hour (VAh) units measure the vector sum of active and reactive energy, provides overall view of energy flow.

apparent.name: Apparent
apparent.description: Apparent energy is the vector sum of active and reactive energy. Although not directly billed, high levels may necessitate system upgrades, leading to additional costs. Generally quantified in kilovolt-ampere-hours (kVAh).

energy.name: Energy
energy.description: Energy in an AC system quantifies the total work done over a period. It encompasses active, reactive, and apparent energy components.

ac.name: AC System
ac.description: AC (Alternating Current), common in power grids, facilitate the long-distance transmission of electricity and is the standard for household and commercial electrical outlets.

temperature.name: Temperature
temperature.description:
Numeric values representing heat level. Measured in specified units like Celsius, Fahrenheit, or Kelvin.
> **Unit:** 
>
>Celsius (°C)
>
>Celsius, also known as centigrade, is a scale and unit of measurement for temperature.

anyOf.name: Low input
anyOf.description: Enough input data to do the calculation but no enough for high accuracy

anyOf.name: Low weather
anyOf.description: Don't have enough weather data to do the calculation but no enough for high accuracy

anyOf.name: Bad model fit
anyOf.description: Model fit is for some reason bad, and caution should be taken with regard to its accuracy and decisions made based on it
